So in summary most of this seems pretty self serving and doesn’t really address the issues that have led to our modern internet.

8: Interoperability

I can be behind this without caveat.

7: Decentralization

I can get behind this as well but the things they mention are very minimal and not true decentralization.

6: Net Neutrality

This I can get behind without caveats.

5: Intermediary Liability Protection

This is just entirely self serving for large firms I don’t see how it advantages smaller firms to have 3rd party liability protection. Especially since this is the current state of things.

4: Effective Competition

Agreed that “competition” is what I want to see ie the internet not being dominated by a handful of firms but their implied solution is zero regulation which will not achieve this.

3: Consumer Choice & Transparency

Again on the surface transparent insight into algorithms that govern these sites sounds good but framing it as consumers choice is sus

2: Non-Binary Content Regulation

Nothing wrong with having more approaches to objectionable content than leave it up or take it down. But we already have this and I don’t see how this is an issue that favours larger firms.

1: Regional & Global Regulatory Alignment

In general I’m all for a single internet that is the same for all users but this is largely impossible while modern states exist.

I definitely don’t trust Twitter to be leading this charge.
